Overall, federal laws on crime and drugs are not usually based on sound analysis of the data. In Congress, "rationality has taken a back seat to politics."1 Most policy on crime and drugs is driven by the need to produce "get tough" rhetoric for the next election cycle. It is no coincidence that almost every omnibus crime control bill passed in the past two decades became law during an election year ? usually

within months, or weeks, of that year's election.

Federal laws to increase sentence length ancybr

