perception of their constituents' fear of crime and desire to feel safe in their communities. The atten

dant rhetoric generated on the House and Senate floor plays very well during campaigns. Especially noteworthy is the amount of floor time spent repeatedly on anecdotal horrific state crimes to justify enactment of federal law.
Similar to the nuclear buildup of decades past, where one could never have too many weapons, there is no limit to the harsh sentences and prison construction that will suffice to make people feel safe. Unfortunately, at the rate we are federalizing crimes and building prisons in the United States, it may well take a Republican with impeccable law and order credentials to bring sanity to the debate on crime and punishment.
The politics of federal sentencing on crack are but a microcosm of the larger debate on crime and drugs. In order to eliminate the disparity in sentenc ing through increasing the amount of crack required to trigger mandatory minimum sentences, it is necessary to create a political climate that allows

Members of Congress to change the law. Some Members who want to "do the right thing" need political cover, although most want to appear respon sive to their constituents. The only way to get their votes is by activating a constituency to whom Con gress is inclined to be responsive. More studies and more data and more op-eds by the same people are not going to make that happen.
The Crack-Cocaine Disparity Possession of more than 5 grams of crack is punish able by a minimum of 5 years in prison; simple possession (without intent to distribute) of any quantity of powder by first offenders is a misde meanor punishable by no more than 1 year in pri son.2 A ten-year mandatory minimum sentence is triggered by trafficking 50 grams of crack, but one must traffic 5000 grams of powder cocaine to trigger the same sentence.3 In 1993, 88.3 percent of those sentenced for trafficking crack were African Ameri can; 4.1 percent were white.4 Although more white Americans use and sell drugs than minorities, far smaller proportions of whites than blacks are arres ted, prosecuted, convicted and incarcerated for drug offenses.5 When fewer numbers of drug offenders are locked up, they are likely to be higher level dealers, since most judges sentence such offenders to prison. But as the number of drug arrests increases, far more small-time users and dealers will be brought within the system.
Congress first enacted harsh mandatory mini mum sentences for crack in 1986, with little scientific data about the drug, with little debate, and in the midst of media-influenced hysteria following the death of basketball star Len Bias, who was assumed to
have died of a crack overdose. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 established mandatory minimum penalties for persons convicted of trafficking in a variety of controlled substances, including the 100-to-i ratio between powder and crack cocaine.6
As detailed by the U.S. Sentencing Commission in its 1995 Special Report to Congress ("the 1995 Report"),7 the Bias autopsy revealed that in fact he had died from a powder cocaine overdose.8 The corrected information, however, did not warrant front-page news coverage, or a reassessment of the subsequent federal sentencing policy. Instead, subsequent election years led to increasingly harsher sentences. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 created the mandatory minimum for simple possession of

