Representative Charles Rangel (D-NY) intro duced "The Crack-Cocaine Equitable Sentencing Act of 1993" (H.R.3277) to eliminate the disparity between sentences for powder and crack by increasing the quantity of crack required to trigger a mandatory sentence. This bill was incorporated into "The Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice Reform Act" (H.R.3315), the omnibus crime control bill drafted on behalf of the Congressional Black Caucus and introduced by Reps. Craig Washington (D-TX), Don Edwards (D-CA), John Conyers (D-MI) and others. When the House Judiciary Committee began consideration of the Administration's omnibus crime
bill (introduced by then-Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joe Biden and House Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks), various elements of the Congressional Black Caucus's Crime Bill were introduced as Amendments, including the Rangel bill on the equitable sentencing of crack and cocaine.
But the Rangel bill could not make it out of committee. There were not enough votes in the Democratically controlled Judiciary Committee despite the fact that Subcommittee Chairman Bill Hughes ? former prosecutor and moderate Democrat from New Jersey ?led the charge. Representative Charles Schumer (D-NY) would have considered a bill to achieve parity if the amount of powder cocaine required for a mandatory minimum sentence were reduced to equal that required for crack. In other words, he wanted to achieve parity by locking up hundreds of young white kids for using small amounts of powder cocaine. Senator Carol Mosley Braun suggested a similar "solution" when she was approached to discuss potential amendments on the Senate floor.
Ultimately, Representative Hughes brought the Rangel bill to the floor of the House during debate on the omnibus crime bill in 1994.10 A formal colloquy with Representative Brooks ensured that the Amendment was pulled and replaced with the standard legislative solution to a difficult issue: a congressional request for a study.
The resulting 1995 Report from the Sentencing Commission proposed a change in the sentencing guidelines to eliminate the differential treatment between crack and powder cocaine offenses in setting base sentences. The Report also recommended that Congress eliminate the differential treatment in the mandatory minimum statutes. The Department of Justice immediately sent draft legislation to Congress to overturn the Commission's proposals. For the first time since the enactment of the guidelines, Congress in October 1995 failed to adopt the Commission's

proposed guideline amendments. Congress asked the Commission to take another look at the issue and
report back, but this time with non-binding recom mendations. Pursuant to Public Law No. 104-38,me Sentencing Commission in April 1997 submitted another Special Report to the Congress: Cocaine and Federal Sentencing Policy ("the 1997 Report").
The 1997 Report recommended that the triggering amount for a 5-year mandatory minimum sentence for crack be changed from the current 5 grams to somewhere in the range of 25-75 grams; and that the triggering amount for a 5-year mandatory sentence for powder cocaine be changed from the current 500 grams to somewhere in the range of 125 375 grams. In other words, the 1997 Report seemed to advocate replacing the current 100:1 ratio between crack and powder with a 5:1 quantity ratio between the two.
Somehow in the two-year interval between 1995 and 1997, the Sentencing Commission found that its analysis of the data which had justified sentencing parity in 1995 now permitted a slight disparity between crack and powder due to the systemic violence associated with multiple and anonymous drug sales of crack markets. Incidentally, the Commission reached this conclusion despite the fact that the sentencing guidelines were designed to take just such factors into account. Since the data had not changed, other factors must have intervened ?e.g., a change in the composition of the Sentencing Commission or a different perspective as to what can affect congres sional action.
Since the Sentencing Commission was not set up to function as an advocate, but rather as an indepen dent body to provide information and recommenda tions to Congress, it has limited experience in strategizing to achieve its goals when they are at odds with Congress's interests.
Strategies for Bringing About an Effective and Just
Crime Policy Timing is critical to the federal legislative process. As discussed above, crime bills usually move during election years when Members of Congress stand the most to gain by focusing on crime and drugs.
Crime rates have been dropping in most major U.S. cities over the past 5 years. It is often politically useful to credit increased sanctions for this turn
around, despite a variety of other potential factors such as an improved economy and changing demogra phics. Crediting "get tough" crime policy helps justify the status quo, or the enactment of more mandatory sentences. There is no reason to question policies that are "working." If, on the other hand, crime were rising, the analysis could be inverted to justify more prisons and harsher sentencing policy.

