The importance of appearing harsh on crime cannot be over-estimated in a tough race for an upcoming election. Ever since the "successful" Willie Horton advertisements helped spell doom for the Dukakis Presidential Campaign, more and more cam paign advertising has focused on the other candidate's history of apparent responsiveness to crime, or lack thereof. Most Members of Congress are only too aware that any action ? especially a vote ? which can be used against them in campaign advertisements usually will be. The rhetoric is just too appealing.
There are exceptions. Whereas every Member of the House is up for election every two years, only one third of the Senate is running for re-election at any given time. Sometimes that extra time liberates Senators. In addition, a small group of Members can afford to vote their conscience. They are either elec ted from safe districts or so principled on particular issues that their stance is tolerated by their constitu ents. This is even more so when they have announced retirement plans (e.g., Representative Hughes' position on crack in 1993 may in part be attributed to his retirement at the end of that Congressional Session). If the goal is to make it possible for Mem bers of Congress to vote to change sentencing policy, some will need political cover, but most will need pressure. This can be achieved in a variety of ways.
First, legislation that will be perceived as "soft" has a better chance of passage if coupled with "get tough" legislation in other areas of criminal law. For example, the Violent and Repeat Juvenile Offender Act of 1997 (S.io) currently before Congress provides just such an opportunity, as it would greatly limit the discretionary nature of the entire juvenile justice system while treating an increasing number of kids as adults so as to subject them to mandatory penalties. Such "tough" legislation could be combined with a "soft" drug bill. Stand-alone bills, however, force votes that few Members of Congress can afford to risk.
Second, bipartisan legislation, especially under a Republican-controlled Congress, has a much better chance of success. Moderate Republicans are often in the best position to take the lead. Historically, Senators Charles "Mac" Mathias (R-MD) and Lowell Weicker (R-CT) successfully championed rational criminal justice policy. Former prosecutors and members of the Senate Judiciary Committee Mike DeWine (R-OH) and Arlen Specter (R-PA) have advo cated for drug courts, alternatives to incarceration, and treatment in prison. While progressive Demo crats can make great policy statements, they are rarely able to move the legislative body on principle alone.
Third, Members' constituents who want change serve as the best kind of cover for a vote ? they provide the political pressure to which the Member must be responsive. Constituents of an issue are

usually defined as consumers, but consumers of crime and drug policy are not usually effective advocates, and often they are not well-positioned to drive policy and effect changes. In particular, it is not easy to motivate the constituents who live in key Members' Districts to advocate for a rational federal
sentencing policy on cocaine. What's in it for them? Nevertheless, even non-voters who pressure for
change can provide some cover if they are viewed as credible. For example, those professionals whose work is affected by the current sentencing policy on cocaine ? such as prosecutors, district attorneys, and police ? have enormous credibility in Congress because they are generally viewed as realistic and unbiased; they "tell it like it is." Law enforcement's role as an
advocate for stronger gun control laws over the past few years provides a good example of Congress's responsiveness to such constituencies.
Strategizing for a New Crack/Cocaine Policy Due to the small qualities which trigger mandatory sentences, the current federal sentencing laws on crack focus on low-end dealers and users, not the
kingpins responsible for moving large quantities of drugs. Yet, when Congress established 5-year manda tory minimum sentences, Members said they wanted them to apply to a mid-level or serious dealers. It is also in the interests of law enforcement to target high-end dealers so as to receive valuable information about high-level operations.
Obviously, on policy issues the White House is responsive to polls in general, and President Clinton has redirected the Democratic Party with poll numbers in mind. This has been particularly true on issues of crime and drugs. One of his first articulated priorities was to take back the crime issue from the Republicans. When the debate on cocaine policy is viewed within that context, it becomes clear that any solution which would reduce the mandatory nature of federal sentencing policy is simply not an option. On the other hand, parity achieved by decreasing the amount of powder required to trigger mandatory sentencing ? such as S.260 introduced by Senator Abraham (R-MI) ? has the potential to reduce disparity but maintain the mandatory sentencing structure.
That the Administration has not always spoken with one voice on the issue should not come as a
surprise. It is due in large part to competing interests in an ever-changing environment. The Justice Department's goals have changed over time and reflect differences among political and career employees. While the Department has multiple objectives, in general it would prefer to keep the U.S. Attorneys happy, maintain primacy over crime and drug policy, and devise legislation based on an inherent difference between powder and crack.

