The Office of National Drug Control Policy became involved in the crack-cocaine issue when
former Director Lee P. Brown supported the recommendations in the 1995 Sentencing Commis sion Report and advocated a redesign of the sentenc ing guidelines so as to take into account any inherent systemic difference between powder and crack, such as violence. Current Director Barry McCaffrey has also played an important role on this issue and has helped move the White House away from the Administration's earlier attack on the 1995 Report, forging a temporary partnership with a Department of Justice that also endorses a significantly reduced ratio.
But in the current political climate the Administration's new position ? although welcome ? does not appear to be sufficient to significantly change the debate in Congress. To eliminate or significantly reduce the disparity in federal sentencing policy on cocaine, the political climate to which Congress responds must be changed.
The focus should be on motivating constituen cies, such as voters in key Congressional Districts. Other voices from the criminal justice system must be heard on the issue: judges and prosecutors as well as defense attorneys and law enforcement profes sionals who know that such disparate sentencing is unworkable must speak up. But the reality is that the state level is one step removed from federal legisla tion, and professionals at the state and local level do not necessarily choose to get involved on federal policy matters. A successful strategy has to take this situation into account by demonstrating the potential impact of federal policy on state and local government.
The racial component of the sentencing policy on cracl^cocaine often serves to bring attention and public debate. However, when this issue is framed primarily as one of race, only 80 Members of Congress will vote accordingly. While such a vote may provide a welcome opportunity for public debate, it can also be polarizing. When true parity in sentencing is framed as the only just position, any argument that does not acknowledge race is at risk.
In order to change current sentencing laws it may be more politically realistic to argue that high-end drug dealers must become the primary targets of federal sentencing laws. After such a reframing of the
issue, an active constituency seeking change could then force a strategic compromise of changed ratios. The pending omnibus juvenile crime bill might provide an opportunity to increase judicial discretion in this area, for example, by expanding the safety valve for non-violent offenses to include low-level crack
offenders. Solely forcing up or down votes in Con gress on the current sentencing structure in the present political climate is unlikely to lead to much change in the near future.

